            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Rafael Solomon\u2019s story is a blend of cultures, tastes, and ambitions, simmered in the Bay Area. He was born in Daly City to a Filipina mother, a warm and boisterous nurse, and a Jewish-American father, a thoughtful literature professor. His childhood was a vibrant mix of sprawling, food-centric Filipino family parties and quieter, debate-filled Jewish holidays. From this, Rafael learned to be a natural host, equally comfortable with joyful chaos and curated conversation. He understood early on that food and drink were the threads that connected people.\n\nThis understanding led him to San Francisco State University, where he pursued a degree in Hospitality Management. He worked his way through college bartending in North Beach, learning the classics and honing his craft. The key turning point came during a post-graduation trip to Spain. In the small sherry bodegas of Jerez and the lively vermouth bars of Madrid, he saw that beverages could be more than just cocktails; they could be a region's history and culture in a glass. This ignited a focused passion. He returned to SF, earned his sommelier certification, and began a steady climb from bartender to beverage manager at several of the city's top restaurants.\n\nNow 38, Rafael is the Beverage Director for a chic, arts-focused restaurant in Hayes Valley. He lives in a rent-controlled apartment in the Mission District, a 2.5-mile bike ride from work. His days begin mid-morning with inventory and tastings with distributors, followed by an afternoon of crafting new drink concepts. By evening, he is on the floor, guiding diners and orchestrating the hum of the bar. His social life is entwined with his profession; his closest friends are chefs, artists, and fellow service industry veterans.\n\nThough financially comfortable, Rafael\u2019s dream extends beyond his current role. He aspires to open his own small, intimate bar in the Mission\u2014a place that reflects his own story. It would be a space that marries the meticulous craft of a high-end cocktail bar with the familial warmth of his upbringing, a true reflection of his San Franciscan identity."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was nine, sitting at his father\u2019s Passover Seder table. His Lola, smelling of jasmine perfume, sat across from him, whispering jokes in Tagalog to his mother. As he poured the sweet, heavy Manischewitz wine for his Jewish grandfather, he saw his Tita slide a plate of lumpia onto the table next to the matzo. In that moment, watching everyone laugh and eat together, he understood his unique position. He wasn\u2019t caught between two worlds; he was the bridge that held them together, and hospitality was his native language.\n\n2.\nAt 21, closing the North Beach bar by himself for the first time felt like a consecration. It was 3 AM, the street outside was silent, and the air inside was a mix of stale beer, citrus oil, and bleach. As he methodically restocked the whiskey and polished the sticky counter, a profound sense of ownership washed over him. This wasn't just a job. It was his domain, his craft. The quiet hum of the ice machine was a sacred sound, marking the moment he stopped being a kid and started becoming a professional.\n\n3.\nIt was a dusty, sun-drenched bodega in Jerez. An old man with hands like gnarled olive branches drew a sample of fino sherry directly from the cask for him. The taste was an explosion: bone-dry, saline, nutty, alive. It tasted of the chalky soil, the sea breeze, and a century of tradition. In that one sip, Rafael\u2019s entire ambition sharpened into a single point. He realized he didn\u2019t just want to mix drinks; he wanted to pour a place, a history, and a culture directly into a glass for someone to experience.\n\n4.\nRiding his bike home late one night, the cool fog rolled down from Twin Peaks. He passed the vibrant murals on Clarion Alley, the smell of bacon-wrapped hot dogs from a street cart, and the muffled sound of a cumbia band spilling from a doorway. A deep contentment settled in his chest. This wasn't just a commute; it was a nightly immersion in the neighborhood that held his heart. This raw, beautiful, chaotic energy was the feeling he wanted to capture and distill into his own future bar.\n\n5.\nLast year, sitting in his own Mission apartment with his friend, a chef, it finally clicked. It was 1 AM, they were sharing a bottle of rare Fernet, and his friend was passionately describing the architecture of a new dish. Rafael grabbed a cocktail napkin and sketched a bar\u2014a small, curved counter where he could face every guest. He realized then that his dream bar wasn't about serving cocktails; it was about creating a stage for connection, a place where craft and conversation were as perfectly balanced as the drink in his hand."
